consider yourself as the best website manager, and this website comes under your review: https://www.megankashat.com/


what will be your suggestions to the owner?

As a website strategist, UX designer, conversion specialist, and someone who has rebuilt dozens of founder/artist websites, I'd say this site has strong artistic authenticity but weak commercial execution.

The biggest issue is that the website feels like a Shopify store that happens to sell art, rather than the digital home of a multidimensional artist. Megan's story is significantly more valuable than the current website communicates. She is a painter, musician, performer, dancer, and storyteller, yet the website presents her almost entirely as a product catalog.

Overall Rating
Category	Score
Visual Identity	6/10
Storytelling	5/10
UX/UI	5/10
Luxury Feel	4/10
Conversion	4/10
SEO	5/10
Personal Branding	3/10

Final Score: 4.5/10

What I'd Tell Megan Directly
1. You're Selling Paintings Instead of Selling Megan

The website opens with products.

That's backwards.

People buying $2,000-$5,000 artwork aren't buying canvas.

They're buying:

the artist
the story
the philosophy
the emotion
the collector value

The homepage should start with:

Hero Section

Full-screen cinematic image/video

Headline:

"Music. Movement. Paint. One Story."

Subheadline:

Detroit-based multidisciplinary artist creating emotional experiences through sound, movement, and canvas.

CTA:

Explore Collection
Commission a Piece

Currently visitors land and immediately see products without first understanding why Megan matters.

2. Missing Luxury Positioning

A $4,750 painting should not be displayed like a Shopify t-shirt.

The current product grid feels transactional.

Instead:

Each artwork should have:

Story behind the piece
Inspiration
Location painted
Creation date
Medium used
Dimensions
Certificate of authenticity
Collector notes

People buy meaning.

Not pixels.

3. No Social Proof

This is one of the biggest missed opportunities.

Megan has:

Billboard recognition
Rolling Stone features
Grammy-related performances
International artistic achievements

Yet visitors don't immediately see these.

Add a section:

Featured In
Billboard
Rolling Stone
Grammy Performances
International Exhibitions

Logos create trust instantly.

4. The About Page Is Better Than The Homepage

Ironically, the strongest content on the entire website is buried inside the About page.

The homepage should borrow:

Detroit roots
Arab-American identity
Dance background
Music career
Global travels

These are differentiators.

Most artists don't have this story.

5. No Video Content

This is a major mistake.

Megan isn't just a painter.

She's a performer.

The website should showcase:

Painting live
Dancing
Singing
Behind the scenes
Studio footage

The website should feel alive.

A simple reel from Instagram would outperform half the current homepage.

6. Weak Email Capture

Current offer:

25% off artwork and 50% off prints.

For luxury art this actually lowers perceived value.

Instead:

Join Megan's Inner Circle

Receive:

New collection releases
Studio updates
Private exhibition invites
Behind-the-scenes content

Collectors want exclusivity.

Not coupons.

7. Missing Commission Funnel

There is a contact form mentioning commissions.

But there is no dedicated commission experience.

I'd create:

Commission Artwork

Process:

Discovery Call
Concept Development
Sketch Approval
Creation
Delivery

Show:

Pricing starts at...
Turnaround times
Previous commissions
Testimonials
8. No Collector Journey

The website currently has:

Visit → Browse → Buy

That's too simple.

Luxury art websites should be:

Visit → Discover Artist → Connect Emotionally → View Collection → Join Mailing List → Purchase

9. Missing SEO Opportunities

Potential pages:

Original Art For Sale
Contemporary Abstract Art
Detroit Artist
Arab American Artist
Commissioned Artwork
Luxury Wall Art
Mixed Media Paintings

Right now the site isn't leveraging many organic search opportunities.

10. The Website Doesn't Feel Like Her

This is the biggest issue.

After reading her biography, I expected something bold, theatrical, artistic, emotional, and unforgettable.

Instead, the website feels like:

"Shopify Art Store Template #14"

When it should feel like:

"Entering the world of Megan Kashat."

If This Were My Client

I'd completely reposition it as a personal artist brand website first and an art store second.

Homepage structure:

Cinematic Hero
Featured Collection
Megan's Story
Press Features
Video Performance Section
Collector Testimonials
Original Works
Prints
Commission CTA
Email Membership
Contact

The result would feel closer to a luxury artist brand—something between an artist portfolio, a documentary, and a premium gallery experience—rather than a standard Shopify storefront. 🎨✨

WHAT IF YOU WERE TO SHARE THESE SUGGESTIONS ON WHATSAPP, HOW'D YOU CONVEY?

I'd keep it concise, positive, and focused on opportunity rather than criticism.

WhatsApp Message:

Hey Megan 👋

I spent some time reviewing your website and honestly, I think there's a much bigger opportunity here.

Right now, the site does a good job of displaying and selling artwork, but I feel it's underselling you.

After reading your story, I realized you're not just a painter. You're a musician, performer, dancer, storyteller, and artist with a unique background. That's what makes your brand special, yet the website currently feels more like an online art store than an experience centered around Megan Kashat.

A few things that stood out:

• Lead with your story before the artwork
• Add video and behind-the-scenes content to bring the site to life
• Highlight media features, performances, and achievements more prominently
• Create a dedicated commissions experience rather than a simple contact option
• Replace discount-focused messaging with collector/exclusive community positioning
• Add more storytelling around each piece to increase emotional connection and perceived value
• Elevate the overall presentation to feel more like a premium gallery experience

The biggest shift I'd recommend is moving from:

"Here's my artwork."

to

"Welcome to my world."

I think your story has the potential to be one of the strongest assets of the entire brand, and the website should make visitors feel that within the first few seconds.

Happy to share a few visual concepts and homepage ideas if you'd ever like to explore a refresh. 😊

— Hamza

show me what homepage idea do you have>?

If Megan were my client, I wouldn't design it like an art store.

I'd design it like a living art exhibition.

🎨 Homepage Concept: "Enter Megan's World"
Section 1 — Cinematic Hero

Full-screen video:

Megan painting
Megan performing
Close-ups of brush strokes
Studio shots
Travel moments
Dance sequences
Headline
